    "\n",
    "#### Question 1: Show that the expected value $E[y]=\\sum y \\cdot P(y)=n \\cdot p_i$\n",
    "\n",
    "To show that the expected value $E[Y]=\\sum y\\cdot P(y)=n \\cdot p$ where $Y$ represents the number of trials for which the outcome falls into a specific cell $i$ with probability $p$, we'll use the properties of expectation.\n",
    "\n",
    "The expected value $E[Y]$ of a random variable $Y$ is defined as the sum of each possible value $Y$ weighted by its probability.\n",
    "\n",
    "Given:\n",
    "\n",
    "- $Y$ is the number of trials  for which the outcome falls into cell $i$\n",
    "- $P(Y=y)$ is the probability that $Y$ takes on the value $y$\n",
    "\n",
    "We want to show that:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "\tE[Y]=\\sum_y y \\cdot  P(Y=y)=n \\cdot p\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "$\n",
    "\n",
    "First, let's consider $P(Y=y)$:\n",
    "\n",
    "Since each trial is independent and the probability of falling into cell $i$ remains the same from trial to trial, we have a binomial distribution. So, $P(Y=y)$ can be calculated using the binomial probability formula:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "\tP(Y=y)=(_y^n) \\cdot p^y \\cdot (1-p)^{n-y}\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "$\n",
    "\n",
    "Now let's calculate the expected value:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\n",
    "\\begin{align}\n",
    "\tE[Y] & =\\sum_y y \\cdot  P(Y=y)\\\\\n",
    "\t& =\\sum_y y \\cdot (_y^n) \\cdot p^y \\cdot (1-p)^{n-y}\n",
    "\\end{align}\n",
    "$\n",
    "\n",
    "Now, we recognize that this is the expansion of the binomial expression $(p+(1-p))^n$, which by the binomial theorem equals 1:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "\t(p+(1-p))^n =1^n=1\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "$\n",
    "\n",
    "So, when we sum over all possible values of y, we get:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\n",
    "\\begin{align}\n",
    "\tE[Y] & =\\sum_y (_y^n) \\cdot p^y \\cdot (1-p)^{n-y} \\cdot y\\\\\n",
    "\t& =n \\cdot p \\cdot \\sum_y (_{y-1}^{n-1}) \\cdot p^{y-1} \\cdot (1-p)^{(n-1)-(y-1)}\\\\\n",
    "\t& =n \\cdot p \\cdot (p+(1-p))^{n-1}\\\\\n",
    "\t& =n \\cdot p\n",
    "\\end{align}\n",
    "$\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Question 2: Given the following data:\n",
    "\n",
    "If 500 adults are sampled randomly, find the probability that the sample contains 100 person between 18 and 24, 200 between, 200 between the ages of 25 and 34, and 200 between the ages of 45 and 64.. What is the expected value for to obtain a person in the 65 and above?\n",
    "\n",
    "$\n",
    "\\begin{gather}\n",
    "\t\\begin{matrix}\n",
    "\t\t\\begin{array}{c|c}\n",
    "\t\t\tAge    & Proportion \\\\\n",
    "\t\t\t18-24  & 0.18\t\t\\\\\n",
    "\t\t\t25-34  & 0.23\t\t\\\\\n",
    "\t\t\t35-44  & 0.16\t\t\\\\\n",
    "\t\t\t45-64  & 0.27\t\t\\\\\n",
    "\t\t\t65-100 & 0.16\t\t\\\\\n",
    "\t\t\\end{array}\n",
    "\t\\end{matrix}\n",
    "\\end{gather}\t\n",
    "$\n",
    "\n",
    "To find the probability of obtaining a sample with specific counts of individuals in each age group, we can use the multinomial probability formula.\n",
    "\n",
    "Given that there are 500 adults sampled, we have:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Number of individuals aged 18-24 $(n_1)=100$\n",
    "- Number of individuals aged 25-34 $(n_2)=200$\n",
    "- Number of individuals aged 45-64 $(n_3)=200$\n",
    "\n",
    "We want to find the probability of this specific arrangement.\n",
    "\n",
    "The multinomial probability formula is:\n",
    "\t\n",
    "$\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "\tP=\\frac{n!}{n_1! \\cdot n_2! \\cdot n_3!} \\cdot  p_1^{n_1} \\cdot p_2^{n_2} \\cdot p_3^{n_3}\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "$\n",
    "\n",
    "Where:\n",
    "\n",
    "- $n$ is the total number of individuals (500 in this case)\n",
    "- $n_1,n_2,n_3$ are the number of individuals in each category\n",
    "- $p_1,p_2,p_3$ are the probability of selecting an individual from each category\n",
    "\n",
    "Given our data:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\n",
    "\\begin{align}\n",
    "\t& p_1 = 0.18\n",
    "\t& p_2 = 0.23\n",
    "\t& p_3 = 0.27\n",
    "\\end{align}\n",
    "$\n",
    "\n",
    "We can calculate the probabilities:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "\tP=\\frac{500!}{100! \\cdot 200! \\cdot 200!} \\cdot  (0.18)^{100} \\cdot (0.23)^{200} \\cdot (0.27)^{200}\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "$\n",
    "\n",
    "For the expected value of obtaining a person aged 65 and above, it would be the total number of individuals multiplied by the proportion of individuals in that age group. So the expected value would be:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "\t500 \\cdot 0.16=80\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "$\n",
    "\n",
    "### Task 2: Consider the following experiment:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. The experiment consists of a fixed number, $n$, of identical trials.\n",
    "2. Each trial results in one of two outcomes: success, $S$, or failure $F$.\n",
    "3. The probability of success on a single trial is equal to some value $p$ and remains the same from trial to trial. The probability of a failure is equal to $q=(1-p)$.\n",
    "4. The trials are independent.\n",
    "5. The random variable of interest is $Y$, the number of successes observed during the $n$ trials.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Question 1: From the following steps shown above, derive the probability distribution of the experiment.\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Define the Random Variable:\n",
    "\n",
    "\tLet $Y$ be the random variable representing the number of successes observed during the $n$ trials.\n",
    "\n",
    "2. Determine the Probability of Each Outcome:\n",
    "\n",
    "\tWe have two possible outcomes on each trial: success(S) or failure(F).\n",
    "\t- The probability of success on a single trial is $p$\n",
    "\t- The probability of failure on a single trial is $q=(1-p)$.\n",
    "\n",
    "3. Identify the Distribution Type:\n",
    "\n",
    "\tSince each trial has two possible outcomes and the probability of success remains constant across all trials, we use the binomial distribution.\n",
    "\n",
    "4. Use the Probability Mass Function (PMF):\n",
    "\n",
    "\tThe probability mass function of the binomial distribution gives the probability of observing exactly $k$ successes in $n$ trials:\n",
    "\n",
    "\t$\n",
    "\t\\begin{equation}\n",
    "\t\tP(Y=k)=(_k^n) \\cdot p^k \\cdot (1-p)^n-k\n",
    "\t\\end{equation}\n",
    "\t$\n",
    "\n",
    "\twhere $k$ ranges from 0 to $n$.\n",
    "\n",
    "By using this formula, we can find the probability of each distribution of each possible outcome $k$, which forms the the probability distribution of the experiment. This distribution shows the likelihood of observing different numbers of successes in the $n$ trials.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Question 2: Show that the expectation of this probability distribution is $E[y]=\\sum y \\cdot P(y) = np$.\n",
    "\n",
    "To show that the expectation of this probability distribution $E[y]=\\sum y \\cdot P(y) = np$, where $Y$ represents the number of successes observed during the $n$ trials, we will utilize the properties of expectation and the probability mass function (PMF) of the binomial distribution.\n",
    "\n",
    "The expectation $E[Y]$ of a random variable $Y$ is defined as the sum of each possible value of $Y$ weighted by its probability.\n",
    "\n",
    "Given:\n",
    "\n",
    "- $Y$ is the number of successes observed during the $n$ trials.\n",
    "- $P(Y=y)$ is the probability that $Y$ takes on the value $y$.\n",
    "\n",
    "We want to show that:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "\tE[Y]=\\sum_y y \\cdot P(Y=y)=np\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "$\n",
    "\n",
    "Then, recall the PMF of the binomial distribution:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "\tP(Y=k)=(_k^n) \\cdot p^k \\cdot (1-p)^n-k\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "$\n",
    "\n",
    "Now, let's calculate the expected value:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\n",
    "\\begin{align}\n",
    "E[Y] & =\\sum_y y \\cdot P(Y=y) \\\\\n",
    "& =\\sum_y y \\cdot (_y^n) \\cdot p^y \\cdot (1-p)^{n-y}\\\\\n",
    "& =\\sum_y y \\cdot \\frac{n!}{y! \\cdot (n-y)!} \\cdot p^y \\cdot (1-p)^{n-y}\\\\\n",
    "& =\\sum_y y \\cdot \\frac{n!}{(y-1)! \\cdot (n-y)!} \\cdot p^y \\cdot (1-p)^{n-y}\\\\\n",
    "& =np \\cdot \\sum_y y \\cdot \\frac{n!}{(y-1)! \\cdot (n-1)-(y-1)!} \\cdot p^{(y-1)} \\cdot (1-p)^{(n-1)-(y-1)}\\\\\n",
    "& =np \\cdot (p+(1-p))^{(n-1)}\\\\\n",
    "& =np\n",
    "\\end{align}\n",
    "$\n",
    "\n",
    "Thus, we have shown that $E[Y]=np$. This means that the expected value of the number of successes in $n$ trials is equal to the product of the number of trials $n$ and the probability of success $p$.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Question 3: Experience has shown that 30% of all persons afflicted by a certain illness recover. A drug company has developed a new medication. Ten people with the illness were selected at random and received the medication; nine recovered shortly thereafter. Suppose that the medication was absolutely worthless. What is the probability that at least nine of ten receiving the medication will recover?\n",
    "\n",
    "To find the probability that at least nine out of ten people receiving the medication will recover, assuming the medication is absolutely worthless, we can use the binomial distribution.\n",
    "\n",
    "Given:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Probability of recovery for each individual with the illness (assuming the medication is worthless): $p=0.30$\n",
    "- Number of trials (people receiving the medication): $n=10$\n",
    "\n",
    "We want to find $P(Y \\geq 9)$, where $Y$ is the number of people recovering out of the ten who received the medication.\n",
    "\n",
    "We'll calculate this by summing the probabilities of exactly 9 recoveries and exactly 10 recoveries.\n",
    "\n",
    "$\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "\tP(Y \\geq 9)=P(Y=9)+P(Y=10)\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "$\n",
    "\n",
    "The probability mass function (PMF) for the binomial distribution is:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "\tP(Y=k)=(_k^n) \\cdot p^k \\cdot (1-p)^{n-k}\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "$\n",
    "\n",
    "So, for $P(Y=9)$:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "\tP(Y=9)=(_9^{10}) \\cdot (0.30)^9 \\cdot (1-0.30)^{10-9}\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "$\n",
    "\n",
    "And for $P(Y=10)$:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "\tP(Y=10)=(_{10}^{10}) \\cdot (0.30)^{10} \\cdot (1-0.30)^{10-10}\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "$\n",
    "\n",
    "Now let's calculate:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\n",
    "\\begin{align}\n",
    "\tP(Y \\geq 9) & =(_9^{10}) \\cdot (0.30)^9 \\cdot (1-0.30)^1+(_{10}^{10}) \\cdot (0.30)^{10} \\cdot (1-0.30)^0\\\\\n",
    "\t& =10 \\cdot (0.30)^9 \\cdot (0.70)+(0.30)^{10}\\\\\n",
    "\t& =10 \\cdot (0.00000000189) \\cdot (0.70)+(0.000000000001)\\\\\n",
    "\t& \\approx 0.0000000132\n",
    "\\end{align}\n",
    "$\n",
    "\n",
    "So, the probability that at least nine out of ten people receiving the medication will recover if the medication is absolutely worthless is approximately $0.0000000132$.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Question 4: Suppose that a lot of 5000 electrical fuses contains 5% defectives. If a sample of 5 fuses is tested, find the probability of observing at least one defective.\n",
    "\n",
    "To find the probability of observing at least one defective fuse in a sample of 5 fuses, we can use the complement rule. The complement of the event \"at least one defective fuse\" is the event \"no defective fuses.\"\n",
    "\n",
    "Let's denote:\n",
    "\n",
    "- $p$ as the probability of a fuse being defective, which is 0.05 in this case.\n",
    "- $q$ as the probability of a fuse being non-defective, which is $1-p=1-0.05=0.95$\n",
    "- $n$ as the number of fuses in the sample, which is 5 in this case.\n",
    "\n",
    "We'll use the binomial probability formula to calculate the probability of observing no defective fuses:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "\tP(X=0)=(_0^n) \\cdot p^0 \\cdot q^n\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "$\n",
    "\n",
    "Where:\n",
    "\n",
    "- $(_0^n)$ is the number of combinations of choosing 0 defective fuses out of $n$ fuses.\n",
    "- $p^0$ is the probability of no defective fuses.\n",
    "- $q^n$ is the probability of all fuses being non-defective.\n",
    "\n",
    "Then the probability of observing at least one defective fuse is:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "\tP(1) = 1-P(0)\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "$\n",
    "\n",
    "First let's calculate the probability of observing no defective fuses:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\n",
    "\\begin{align}\n",
    "\tP(0) & =(_0^5) \\cdot (0.05)^0 \\cdot (0.95)^5\\\\\n",
    "\t& =1 \\cdot 1 \\cdot (0.95)^5\\\\\n",
    "\t& =1 \\cdot 1 \\cdot 0.77378\\\\\n",
    "\t& \\approx 0.77378\n",
    "\\end{align}\n",
    "$\n",
    "\n",
    "Now let's find the probability of observing at least one defective fuse:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\n",
    "\\begin{align}\n",
    "\tP(1) & =1-P(0)\\\\\n",
    "\t& =1-0.77378\\\\\n",
    "\t& \\approx 0.22622\n",
    "\\end{align}\n",
    "$\n",
    "\n",
    "So, the probability of observing at least one defective fuse in a sample of 5 fuses is approximately 0.22622%\n",
    "\n",
    "### Task 3: Consider a probability distribution of $p(y)=\\frac{\\lambda y}{y!} e^-\\lambda$.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Question 1: Find a general formula for the expected value of this distribution.\n",
    "\n",
    "To find the expected value (mean) of the given probability distribution $p(y)=\\frac{\\lambda^y}{y!}e^{-\\lambda}$, we'll use the definition of expectation.\n",
    "\n",
    "The expected value $E[Y]$ of a random variable $Y$ with the probability mass function $p(y) is calculated as:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "\tE[Y]=\\sum_{y=0}^\\infty y \\cdot p(y)\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "$\n",
    "\n",
    "Given the probability mass function:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "\tp(y)=\\frac{\\lambda^y}{y!}e^{-\\lambda}\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "$\n",
    "\n",
    "We can substitute this into the formula for the expected value:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "\tE[Y]=\\sum_{y=0}^\\infty y \\cdot \\frac{\\lambda^y}{y!}e^{-\\lambda}\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "$\n",
    "\n",
    "We can simplify this expression further by considering the definition of the exponential function:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "\te^x=\\sum_{n=0}^\\infty \\frac{x^n}{n!}\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "$\n",
    "\n",
    "Now, we can rewrite the probability mass function in terms of the exponential function:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\n",
    "\\begin{align}\n",
    "\tp(y) & =\\frac{\\lambda^y}{y!}e^{-\\lambda}=e^{-\\lambda} \\cdot \\frac{\\lambda^y}{y!} \\\\\n",
    "\t& e^{-\\lambda} \\cdot \\frac{1}{y!} \\cdot  (\\lambda^y)\n",
    "\\end{align}\n",
    "$\n",
    "\n",
    "This looks similar to the expansion of $e^x$, where $x=\\lambda$. So, we can rewrite it as:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "\tp(y)=e^{-\\lambda} \\cdot \\frac{\\lambda^y}{y!}\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "$\n",
    "\n",
    "This is precisely the probability mass function of a Poisson distribution with paramater $\\lambda$. Therefore, the expected value of this is distribution is simply $\\lambda$.\n",
    "\n",
    "Hence, the general formula for the expected value of this distribution is:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "\tE[Y]=\\lambda\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "$\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Question 2: A certain type of tree has seedlings randomly dispersed in a large area, with the mean density of seedlings being approximately five per square yard. If a forester randomly locates ten 1-square-yard sampling regions in the area, find the probability that none of the regions will contain seedlings.\n",
    "\n",
    "To find the probability that none of the ten 1-square-yard sampling regions contain seedlings, we can use the Poisson distribution, as the given scenario follows a Poisson process.\n",
    "\n",
    "Given:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Mean density of seedlings: $\\lambda=5$ seedlings per square yard.\n",
    "- Number of sampling regions:$n=10$\n",
    "- Probability of observing $k$ seedlings in a 1-square-yard sampling region: $p(k)=\\frac{\\lambda^k}{k!}e^{-\\lambda}$\n",
    "\n",
    "We want to find the probability of observing 0 seedlings in each of the ten sampling regions. Since the events are independent, we can simply multiply the probabilities together.\n",
    "\n",
    "The probability of observing 0 seedlings in 1-square-yard region is given by $p(0)$:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "\tp(0)=\\frac{5^0}{0!}e^{-5}=e^{-5}\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "$\n",
    "\n",
    "Therefore, the probability that none of the ten regions contain seedlings is:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "\tp(0) \\approx 0.00673794699\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "$\n",
    "\n",
    "So, the probability that none of the regions will contain seedlings is approximately 0.0067%."
